ce:section.ce:para:
In this work, we obtain the long-wavelength emission solid-state CDs with remarkable thermal stability. In contrast to previous works using conventional silica materials, the novel nanoporous glass (NPG) is designed to disperse the solid-state CDs in the three-dimensional (3D) confined space. Very recently, E. A. Stepanidenko et al. [30] demonstrated that the nanoporous silicate glass as the silicate matrix, can efficiently preserve and even enhance the emission of carbon dots, in contrast to the quenched emission of CD films drop-casted directly onto glass slides. Even if the wavelengths of lecture [30] are at the blue-green band. Therefore, materials with well-designed 3D structures have attracted lots of attention, e.g., a delicate three-dimensional (3D) structure of graphene is used to improve the mechanical strength [31]. The interaction between nanoparticles is proved to be efficient in tuning the absorption and emission wavelength of the materials [32,33]. The properties can be further used in the detection of specific particles [34]. By regulating the ratio of boron to silicon, the sizes of the pores in NPG and CDs are designed to be precisely matched. Based on the proposed preparation method, the CDs are not only isolated due to the physical structure of NPG at the nanoscale but also dispersed with the formed -C-O-Si functional groups. As a result, the AIQ problem of the solid-state CDs is significantly eased and the PL intensity is enhanced. More importantly, the CDs-in-NPG have excellent thermal stability. As illustrated in Fig. 1
                     , the highlights of the prepared CDs-in-NPG include:

                           •

The nanoporous glass (NPG) is firstly used to obtain the fluorescent and thermal stable carbon dots (CDs);


                           •

The emission wavelength of CDs-in-NPG is 609 nm, i.e., the prepared CDs-in-NPG have stable orange fluorescence while the excitation wavelengths range from 260 nm to 560 nm;


                           •

The PL intensity of CDs-in-NPG improves up to 91.7 times and the PL lifetime elevates more than 10%, compared to the pristine CDs;


                           •

The CDs-in-NPG still preserve the ability to emit strong orange-light under high temperature up to 400 °C while other orange emission solid-state CDs are damaged over 100 °C.
